  "prompt": "What is indirect recursion?",
  "response": "Indirect recursion occurs when a function is called not directly by itself, but through another function. This involves a cycle where two or more functions call each other in a loop. For instance, function `A` might call function `B`, and function `B` might call function `A`, creating an indirect cycle. This contrasts with direct recursion, where a function calls itself directly.\n\nHere's a simple example of indirect recursion:\n\n```python\ndef function_a(x):\n    if x > 0:\n        print(\"A:\", x)\n        function_b(x - 1)\n\ndef function_b(x):\n    if x > 0:\n        print(\"B:\", x)\n        function_a(x - 1)\n\n# Start the indirect recursion\nfunction_a(3)\n```\n\nIn this example, `function_a` calls `function_b`, and `function_b` calls `function_a`. The recursion terminates when `x` is no longer greater than 0. Indirect recursion can be more difficult to track and understand compared to direct recursion, particularly in large codebases with many interconnected functions.",
